full_text:
@Tinu No problem! Just because someone has hearing loss does not mean they immediately learn how to lipread. It takes years to gradually learn. And since I was in oralism focused teachings, this has unfortunately drilled into me.
Remember everyone is different! Even family!
full_text(utf-8): b'@Tinu No problem! Just because someone has hearing loss does not mean they immediately learn how to lipread. It takes years to gradually learn. And since I was in oralism focused teachings, this has unfortunately drilled into me.\nRemember everyone is different! Even family!'

full_text: @Tinu Lipreading is very complex compared to what media and hearing people make you think. It‚Äôs a lot of work for our brains to overwork just to understand.
full_text(utf-8): b'@Tinu Lipreading is very complex compared to what media and hearing people make you think. It\xe2\x80\x99s a lot of work for our brains to overwork just to understand.'

full_text: @Tinu But lipreading is a lot about fitting in context clues. Like finding the vocabulary from what scenario you are in. Like school and work would have different words that are often used. So I kinda plug those options in.
full_text(utf-8): b'@Tinu But lipreading is a lot about fitting in context clues. Like finding the vocabulary from what scenario you are in. Like school and work would have different words that are often used. So I kinda plug those options in.'

full_text: @Tinu Since the mask mandate many people (hearing and HOH) are discovering how much they used to rely on lipreading. Lipreading is something your body kinda learns over time. (Which is why I‚Äôm rather good at it bc I lost my hearing gradually over childhood)
full_text(utf-8): b'@Tinu Since the mask mandate many people (hearing and HOH) are discovering how much they used to rely on lipreading. Lipreading is something your body kinda learns over time. (Which is why I\xe2\x80\x99m rather good at it bc I lost my hearing gradually over childhood)'

full_text: @Tinu Yeah, science says only about 30% of the English language can be read on the lips. (Which is failing in most things) if I have my hearing aid on I find lipreading is helpful. However if I do not, I can‚Äôt usually understand things said.
full_text(utf-8): b'@Tinu Yeah, science says only about 30% of the English language can be read on the lips. (Which is failing in most things) if I have my hearing aid on I find lipreading is helpful. However if I do not, I can\xe2\x80\x99t usually understand things said.'

full_text: So if you are going to adopt, ESPECIALLY outside of your own race, look at stories from adoptees. As we know what it‚Äôs like to live this story. Our parents might have good insight on the process and paperwork, but we are the ones living this.
full_text(utf-8): b'So if you are going to adopt, ESPECIALLY outside of your own race, look at stories from adoptees. As we know what it\xe2\x80\x99s like to live this story. Our parents might have good insight on the process and paperwork, but we are the ones living this.'

full_text:
We grow up just hearing about how we were abandoned and then are institutionalized. Since I was little I knew I was abandoned in a train station. Many disabled adoptees know why we were given up.
It‚Äôs layers of identity crisies that I have only begun unpacking a few years ago.
full_text(utf-8): b'We grow up just hearing about how we were abandoned and then are institutionalized. Since I was little I knew I was abandoned in a train station. Many disabled adoptees know why we were given up.\nIt\xe2\x80\x99s layers of identity crisies that I have only begun unpacking a few years ago.'

full_text:
Especially with transracial adoptees, we face a lot of internalized racism. We face outright racism from those closest to us, often our adopted parents. But we aren‚Äôt given the words or the tools to express that.
Many of us don‚Äôt know our backgrounds, or even our birthdays.
